{
  "When blood glucose is high, the pancreas releases:": "",
  "Glucagon": "",
  "Epinephrine": "",
  "Cortisol": "",
  "Insulin": "",
  "Elevated blood glucose stimulates beta cells of the pancreatic islets to release insulin, which promotes glucose uptake by cells and glycogen storage in the liver, thereby lowering blood sugar levels.": "",
  "When blood glucose is low, the pancreas releases:": "",
  "Calcitonin": "",
  "ADH": "",
  "Low blood glucose stimulates alpha cells in the pancreatic islets to release glucagon, which acts on the liver to promote glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis, raising blood sugar back toward the set point.": "",
  "PTH increases blood calcium by:": "",
  "Excreting calcium through the kidneys": "",
  "Blocking calcium absorption from the intestines": "",
  "Releasing calcium from bone, increasing renal reabsorption, and activating vitamin D": "",
  "Storing calcium in bone matrix": "",
  "PTH raises blood calcium through three complementary mechanisms: stimulating osteoclasts to release calcium from bone, increasing calcium reabsorption in the renal tubules, and activating vitamin D to enhance intestinal calcium absorption.": "",
  "Calcitonin decreases blood calcium by:": "",
  "Promoting calcium deposition into bone and reducing renal reabsorption": "",
  "Releasing calcium from bone into the blood": "",
  "Completely blocking PTH production": "",
  "Converting calcium into phosphorus": "",
  "Calcitonin from the thyroid's parafollicular cells lowers blood calcium by inhibiting osteoclast activity (reducing bone resorption) and decreasing renal tubular reabsorption of calcium, promoting its excretion.": "",
  "ADH is released when:": "",
  "Blood osmolarity is high, such as during dehydration": "",
  "Blood pressure is dangerously high": "",
  "Blood is very dilute with low osmolarity": "",
  "Blood calcium drops below normal": "",
  "Osmoreceptors in the hypothalamus detect increased blood osmolarity (concentrated blood) during dehydration and trigger the release of ADH from the posterior pituitary to promote water retention by the kidneys.": "",
  "ADH causes the kidneys to:": "",
  "Stop all urine production entirely": "",
  "Excrete sodium in large quantities": "",
  "Excrete more water, producing dilute urine": "",
  "Reabsorb more water, producing concentrated urine": "",
  "ADH (antidiuretic hormone) increases the permeability of the collecting ducts in the kidneys by inserting aquaporin channels, allowing more water to be reabsorbed back into the blood and producing less but more concentrated urine.": "",
  "Aldosterone helps regulate blood pressure by:": "",
  "Causing kidneys to retain sodium so water follows, increasing blood volume and pressure": "",
  "Directly dilating blood vessels": "",
  "Lowering heart rate significantly": "",
  "Causing kidneys to excrete sodium rapidly": "",
  "Aldosterone acts on the distal tubules and collecting ducts of the kidneys to promote sodium reabsorption; water follows sodium osmotically, increasing blood volume and consequently raising blood pressure.": "",
  "Cortisol is important during stress because it:": "",
  "Has no measurable effect during stress": "",
  "Lowers blood sugar to conserve energy": "",
  "Increases blood glucose, suppresses inflammation, and mobilizes energy reserves": "",
  "Only affects mood and emotions": "",
  "Cortisol is the body's primary long-term stress hormone, raising blood glucose through gluconeogenesis, suppressing non-essential immune responses, and mobilizing fatty acids and amino acids to provide sustained energy during prolonged stress.": "",
  "The renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system (RAAS) is activated by:": "",
  "High blood calcium levels": "",
  "Elevated blood glucose after a meal": "",
  "High blood pressure detected by baroreceptors": "",
  "Low blood pressure, which causes the kidneys to release renin": "",
  "When blood pressure drops, the juxtaglomerular cells of the kidneys release renin, initiating the cascade: renin converts angiotensinogen to angiotensin I, which is converted to angiotensin II by ACE, ultimately stimulating aldosterone release to raise blood pressure.": "",
  "Erythropoietin (EPO) is released by the kidneys when:": "",
  "Blood glucose is elevated after eating": "",
  "Oxygen levels are low, stimulating red blood cell production": "",
  "Oxygen levels in the blood are high": "",
  "Blood pressure is elevated": "",
  "When renal cells detect hypoxia (low oxygen), they secrete erythropoietin, which travels to the bone marrow and stimulates the production of red blood cells (erythropoiesis), thereby increasing the blood's oxygen-carrying capacity.": "",
  "What is homeostasis?": "",
  "A state of constant change with no regulation": "",
  "A condition where all body systems shut down to conserve energy": "",
  "The process of growing new cells to replace old ones": "",
  "The maintenance of a stable internal environment within a narrow physiological range despite changes in external conditions": "",
  "Homeostasis is the body's ability to maintain stable internal conditions (such as temperature, pH, blood glucose, and fluid balance) within narrow physiological limits through continuous monitoring and adjustment by feedback mechanisms.": "",
  "What does 'gluconeogenesis' mean?": "",
  "The synthesis of new glucose from non-carbohydrate sources such as amino acids, lactate, and glycerol": "",
  "The breakdown of glycogen into glucose molecules": "",
  "The conversion of glucose into fat for storage": "",
  "The absorption of glucose from the intestines into the blood": "",
  "Gluconeogenesis literally means 'new glucose creation' and refers to the metabolic pathway in the liver (and to a lesser extent kidneys) that synthesizes glucose from non-carbohydrate precursors like amino acids, lactate, and glycerol during fasting or stress.": "",
  "What does 'glycogenolysis' mean?": "",
  "The synthesis of glycogen from glucose for storage": "",
  "The breakdown of stored glycogen into glucose to raise blood sugar": "",
  "The excretion of excess glucose through the kidneys": "",
  "The conversion of glycogen into amino acids": "",
  "Glycogenolysis is the metabolic process of breaking down glycogen (the stored form of glucose in the liver and muscles) into individual glucose molecules, which is stimulated by glucagon and epinephrine when blood sugar levels drop.": "",
  "What is the RAAS (renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system)?": "",
  "A system that regulates blood glucose through insulin and glucagon": "",
  "A hormonal cascade activated by low blood pressure in which renin triggers angiotensin production, leading to aldosterone release, sodium retention, and increased blood pressure": "",
  "A hormone cascade that lowers blood pressure by dilating blood vessels": "",
  "A neural reflex that controls heart rate during exercise": "",
  "RAAS is a critical hormonal cascade: low blood pressure triggers renin release from the kidneys, which converts angiotensinogen to angiotensin I, then ACE converts it to angiotensin II (a potent vasoconstrictor), which also stimulates aldosterone to retain sodium and water, raising blood pressure.": "",
  "What is erythropoietin (EPO)?": "",
  "A white blood cell growth factor from the thymus": "",
  "A hormone from the thyroid that increases metabolic rate": "",
  "A hormone produced primarily by the kidneys in response to low oxygen levels that stimulates red blood cell production in the bone marrow": "",
  "An enzyme that breaks down red blood cells in the spleen": "",
  "Erythropoietin is a glycoprotein hormone produced by peritubular cells of the kidney in response to tissue hypoxia that acts on the bone marrow to increase the production and maturation of red blood cell precursors.": "",
  "What does 'antidiuretic' mean in the context of ADH?": "",
  "Promoting urine production to eliminate excess water": "",
  "Blocking all kidney function temporarily": "",
  "Increasing sodium excretion to reduce blood pressure": "",
  "Against (anti-) excessive urine production (diuresis), meaning the hormone reduces urine output by promoting water reabsorption": "",
  "The term antidiuretic means 'against diuresis' (excessive urination); ADH opposes water loss by increasing water permeability in the kidney collecting ducts through aquaporin channel insertion, thereby reducing urine volume and conserving body water.": "",
  "What is insulin resistance?": "",
  "The autoimmune destruction of pancreatic beta cells by T lymphocytes, resulting in absolute insulin deficiency that requires lifelong exogenous insulin replacement therapy": "",
  "A condition where target cells do not respond properly to insulin despite adequate or elevated insulin levels, leading to impaired glucose uptake": "",
  "An allergic hypersensitivity reaction to exogenous insulin injections, causing localized inflammation and tissue necrosis at the injection site": "",
  "A condition where the pancreatic beta cells produce excessive amounts of insulin, leading to chronic hypoglycemia and recurrent episodes of confusion and unconsciousness": "",
  "Insulin resistance is a pathological condition in which cells (especially muscle, liver, and fat) fail to respond normally to insulin signaling, requiring the pancreas to produce more insulin to achieve the same glucose-lowering effect, and is a hallmark of type 2 diabetes.": "",
  "What does 'hypercalcemia' mean?": "",
  "Excessive calcium excretion in the urine": "",
  "Normal calcium levels maintained by homeostasis": "",
  "Abnormally high calcium levels in the blood": "",
  "Abnormally low calcium levels in the blood": "",
  "Hypercalcemia (hyper = excessive, calc = calcium, emia = in the blood) refers to abnormally elevated blood calcium levels, which can result from hyperparathyroidism, certain cancers, or excessive vitamin D intake, potentially causing kidney stones, bone pain, and cardiac arrhythmias.": "",
  "What is osmolarity?": "",
  "The number of red blood cells per liter of blood": "",
  "The measure of blood pressure in arteries": "",
  "The rate at which blood flows through the kidneys": "",
  "The concentration of solute particles dissolved in a solution, used to measure how concentrated the blood is": "",
  "Osmolarity is a measure of solute concentration per liter of solution; blood osmolarity is tightly regulated around 275-295 mOsm/L, and changes are detected by hypothalamic osmoreceptors that trigger ADH release or suppression to maintain water balance.": "",
  "What is a mineralocorticoid?": "",
  "A hormone that regulates blood glucose levels by promoting cellular uptake and hepatic storage of glucose in response to elevated postprandial blood sugar concentrations": "",
  "A type of bone cell embedded in the mineralized matrix that stores calcium and phosphate and helps maintain the structural integrity of the skeletal system": "",
  "A fat-soluble vitamin that enhances the intestinal absorption of dietary calcium and phosphate, working synergistically with parathyroid hormone to maintain mineral homeostasis": "",
  "A class of adrenal cortex steroid hormones, primarily aldosterone, that regulate mineral (electrolyte) balance by controlling sodium and potassium levels": "",
  "Mineralocorticoids are steroid hormones produced by the zona glomerulosa of the adrenal cortex, with aldosterone being the most important, regulating electrolyte balance by promoting sodium retention and potassium excretion in the kidneys.": "",
  "A patient with uncontrolled type 2 diabetes has a fasting blood glucose of 250 mg/dL. The physician explains that the patient's cells are not responding to insulin even though the pancreas is producing it. What is the primary problem in this patient?": "",
  "The patient's pancreas has been destroyed by autoimmune attack": "",
  "The patient's cells are insulin resistant, meaning they do not respond properly to insulin despite its presence": "",
  "The patient's kidneys are excreting all the insulin": "",
  "The patient's liver is producing too much calcitonin": "",
  "In type 2 diabetes, the fundamental problem is insulin resistance: target cells (muscle, liver, fat) have reduced sensitivity to insulin signaling, so glucose cannot efficiently enter cells despite adequate or even elevated insulin levels, leading to persistent hyperglycemia.": "",
  "A marathon runner collapses during a race and is found to have dangerously low blood sodium levels (hyponatremia) from drinking too much water. Which hormone system failed to compensate, and what should it have done?": "",
  "Glucagon should have converted sodium into glucose": "",
  "PTH should have released sodium from bone stores": "",
  "ADH should have been suppressed to allow the kidneys to excrete the excess water, but the runner overwhelmed the system": "",
  "Insulin should have increased sodium absorption from the gut": "",
  "Normally, when blood becomes dilute (low osmolarity), ADH secretion is suppressed so the kidneys excrete excess water; however, the runner consumed water faster than the kidneys could eliminate it, overwhelming the ADH regulatory system and leading to dangerous dilutional hyponatremia.": "",
  "A patient with chronic kidney disease is found to have severe anemia (low red blood cell count). The nephrologist explains that the damaged kidneys can no longer produce adequate amounts of a key hormone. Which hormone is deficient?": "",
  "Erythropoietin (EPO)": "",
  "Aldosterone": "",
  "The kidneys are the primary source of erythropoietin, and chronic kidney disease impairs EPO production, leading to reduced stimulation of red blood cell production in the bone marrow and resulting in anemia of chronic kidney disease.": "",
  "A patient is diagnosed with a parathyroid tumor that is producing excessive PTH. Which of the following would you expect to find on the blood work?": "",
  "Low calcium and low potassium": "",
  "High blood calcium and low blood phosphate due to excessive bone resorption and renal calcium reabsorption": "",
  "Normal calcium with elevated blood glucose": "",
  "Low blood calcium and high blood phosphate": "",
  "Excess PTH (hyperparathyroidism) causes hypercalcemia by increasing osteoclast activity (releasing calcium from bone), increasing renal calcium reabsorption, and activating vitamin D for greater intestinal absorption, while simultaneously increasing phosphate excretion.": "",
  "A medical student is studying a patient who has been taking high-dose prednisone (a synthetic cortisol) for months. The student notes the patient has elevated blood sugar, despite having no prior history of diabetes. What explains this finding?": "",
  "Excess cortisol promotes gluconeogenesis and opposes insulin action, raising blood glucose levels": "",
  "Prednisone stimulates the release of insulin, which raises glucose": "",
  "The patient must have been eating excessive sugar": "",
  "Prednisone destroyed the patient's thyroid gland": "",
  "Cortisol (and its synthetic analog prednisone) is a counter-regulatory hormone that raises blood glucose by stimulating hepatic gluconeogenesis and antagonizing insulin's effects on peripheral tissues, which is why chronic steroid use can cause steroid-induced diabetes.": "",
  "A patient with heart failure is retaining fluid and has dangerously high blood pressure. The cardiologist prescribes an ACE inhibitor. Based on your knowledge of the RAAS, how does this medication lower blood pressure?": "",
  "It stimulates ADH release to dilute the blood": "",
  "It blocks the conversion of angiotensin I to angiotensin II, reducing vasoconstriction and aldosterone release, leading to lower blood pressure": "",
  "It increases renin production to flush out excess sodium": "",
  "It directly destroys aldosterone receptors in the kidneys": "",
  "ACE inhibitors block angiotensin-converting enzyme, preventing the formation of angiotensin II, which is a potent vasoconstrictor and stimulator of aldosterone; without angiotensin II, blood vessels relax, aldosterone decreases, sodium and water are excreted, and blood pressure drops.": "",
  "A hiker becomes severely dehydrated after a long trek without water. Upon reaching the hospital, blood tests show very concentrated blood (high osmolarity). Which hormonal response would the body have initiated to conserve water?": "",
  "Suppression of ADH to produce more dilute urine": "",
  "Release of calcitonin to reduce calcium excretion": "",
  "Increased glucagon release to provide energy": "",
  "Increased ADH release from the posterior pituitary to promote water reabsorption and produce concentrated urine": "",
  "High blood osmolarity from dehydration is detected by hypothalamic osmoreceptors, which trigger increased ADH release from the posterior pituitary; ADH then acts on kidney collecting ducts to insert aquaporin channels, maximizing water reabsorption and producing small volumes of concentrated urine.": "",
  "A patient undergoing surgery develops significant blood loss. The surgical team monitors blood pressure closely. Which hormonal cascade would be activated to help restore blood pressure?": "",
  "The HPT axis to increase thyroid hormone production": "",
  "The insulin-glucagon axis to regulate blood sugar": "",
  "The renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system (RAAS) to promote sodium and water retention and vasoconstriction": "",
  "The calcitonin-PTH axis to mobilize calcium from bone": "",
  "Blood loss reduces blood volume and pressure, which is detected by the juxtaglomerular cells of the kidneys; they release renin, activating the RAAS cascade that produces angiotensin II (vasoconstriction) and stimulates aldosterone (sodium and water retention) to restore blood pressure.": "",
  "A nursing student is caring for a diabetic patient who accidentally injected too much insulin. The patient becomes confused, sweaty, and shaky. What is happening physiologically, and which counter-regulatory hormone should respond?": "",
  "The patient has hypercalcemia, and calcitonin should respond to lower calcium": "",
  "The patient has hypoglycemia from excess insulin, and glucagon from alpha cells should respond to raise blood glucose": "",
  "The patient has hypernatremia, and aldosterone should respond to excrete sodium": "",
  "The patient has hyperglycemia, and ADH should respond to dilute the blood": "",
  "Excess insulin causes hypoglycemia (dangerously low blood sugar), producing symptoms like confusion, sweating, and shakiness; the body's primary counter-regulatory response is glucagon release from pancreatic alpha cells, which stimulates hepatic glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis to raise blood glucose.": "",
  "A physician is explaining to a medical student why a patient with Addison's disease (adrenal insufficiency) has low blood pressure and high potassium levels. Which hormone deficiency best explains both of these findings?": "",
  "Epinephrine deficiency from the adrenal medulla": "",
  "Growth hormone deficiency from the pituitary": "",
  "Insulin deficiency from the pancreas": "",
  "Aldosterone deficiency, which normally promotes sodium retention and potassium excretion to maintain blood pressure": "",
  "Aldosterone deficiency in Addison's disease means the kidneys cannot retain sodium effectively, so sodium and water are lost (causing low blood volume and hypotension), while potassium is not properly excreted (causing dangerous hyperkalemia), explaining both clinical findings.": ""
}